1. The Core Conflict: Fungible vs. Non-Fungible (Identity)
This is the biggest technicalåˆ†æ­§ (divergence) between the two plans.

My Approach (Zai): Fungible Token (ERC-20)
The Concept: Every human gets 1 WILL Token. The token is fungible (interchangeable), but transfer-restricted (Soulbound).
The Logic: This treats "Voting Power" like a currency. You can send 0.5 WILL to Rep A and 0.5 to Rep B.
Pros:
Mathematical Simplicity: Calculating if a Representative has hit a threshold is a simple balanceOf(address) check. It is gas-efficient and standard.
Granular Splitting: Easy to split your vote finely among many issues.
Cons:
Implementation Risk: Creating a "Fungible but Non-Transferable" token is non-standard and requires custom code logic (you have to override the transfer function). If there is a bug, people might trade their votes.
Geminiâ€™s Approach: Non-Fungible Token (NFT)
The Concept: Every human gets a WILL NFT. The NFT represents your Identity/Soul.
The Logic: The NFT itself cannot be split. It acts as a battery that generates "Voting Power" (Credits) over time.
Pros:
Security: NFTs (ERC-721) are natively unique. It is much harder to accidentally code a way to sell your soul (NFT) than it is to mess up transfer restrictions on a coin.
Identity Clarity: It clearly separates Who You Are (NFT) from How You Vote (Credits).
Cons:
Complexity: You now have two layers of state: The NFT (the static voter) and the Credits (the dynamic power). This increases gas costs and code complexity.
ðŸ† Verdict on Identity: Geminiâ€™s NFT approach is safer.
In a political system, preventing the buying and selling of votes is priority #1. An NFT is structurally better at representing a "Soul" or a "Citizenship" than a coin.

2. The Delegation Mechanism
My Approach: Direct Balance Transfer
How it works: You use your wallet to delegate your tokens. The Representative's smart contract balance goes up instantly.
Metaphor: Handing cash to a friend.
Danger: If you delegate to a Representative, and that Representative gets hacked or acts maliciously, your tokens might be stuck or "slashed" (burned) depending on the contract logic.
Geminiâ€™s Approach: Staking / Streaming
How it works: You "Stake" your NFT to the Representative. The Representative earns "Credits" from your staked NFT.
Metaphor: Investing in a company. You own the stock (NFT), but the company (Rep) uses the capital.
Advantage: Recallability. Because you still "hold" the NFT, you can unstake it instantly if the Representative turns bad. In my model, if the contract logic doesn't allow easy undelegation, you might be stuck.
ðŸ† Verdict on Delegation: Geminiâ€™s Staking model is superior for Liquid Democracy.
Liquid Democracy requires that voters can change their minds instantly. Staking allows for a clean "un-stake" if the Representative fails to deliver.

