The "WILL" Protocol v5: The Public Entrepreneur Model
1. The Revised "Economic Sink" (The Royalty Mechanic)
Instead of a "Tax" or "Loan Repayment," we implement a Smart Revenue Royalty.

The Workflow
The Mint: The Representative (Smart Contract) unlocks $1,000,000 to build a "Solar Array."
The Asset Ownership: The assets (Solar Panels, Land, Grid connection) are legally owned by the Smart Contract (not the Representative).
The Revenue Stream: The Solar Array sells electricity to the grid. The money flows automatically into the Smart Contract.
The "Success Split": The code automatically splits the revenue:
100% goes to repay the initial $1,000,000 (Burned upon return to Treasury).
1% (of the total project revenue/lifetime) is diverted to the Representative's personal wallet as a Success Fee.
Surplus: Any remaining profit after the 1% and the principal repayment can be distributed to the Voters (Dividend) or used for the next project.
Why this works:
The Representative is effectively "Skimming the Top" of a productive asset. To get that 1%, the asset must exist and must be generating value. A Representative cannot "embezzle" the construction funds because the funds were likely paid directly to a Whitelisted Contractor in Phase 3. Their only path to wealth is the 1% performance fee.

2. Danger Analysis: The "Cash Cow" Aristocracy
While the 1% incentive solves the motivation problem, it introduces a new danger: The Permanent Rent-Seeker.

The Danger
If a Representative proposes a "Toll Bridge" that costs $10M and generates $1M a year forever, that Representative earns $10,000 a year, forever, without doing any more work.

Over 20 years, they make $200k for one idea.
This creates a class of "Landed Representatives" who sit back and collect passive income while the Voters do the work.
The Fix: The "Sunset Clause" & "Management Fee"
We must prevent passive hoarding of rewards.

Sunset Clause: The 1% Success Fee is not forever. It expires after 3 years or after 200% of the principal has been paid back (whichever comes first).
Re-Application: To keep earning the 1% on the Toll Bridge, the Representative must submit a "Maintenance Proposal" every few years. The Voters must re-delegate their WILL to this Representative to prove the bridge is still being maintained. If Voters withdraw support, the 1% stream stops, and the revenue goes 100% to the Treasury.
3. Danger Analysis: The "Failed Project" (Inflation Leak)
You said the Representative is pleased to pay it back. But what if the project fails and generates $0 revenue?

The Danger
The Solar Array is built but gets destroyed by a storm a week later. No electricity is sold. No revenue comes in.

The Treasury printed $1M.
$0 is paid back.
The $1M remains in the economy, causing permanent inflation.
The Fix: "Skin in the Game" (Staking)
We cannot rely solely on the "pleasure" of repayment. We need a penalty for failure to protect the currency value.

The Requirement: To propose a $1M project, the Representative must Stake $10k of their own money (or a significant amount of WILL tokens).
The Default: If the project fails to generate revenue within a set time (e.g., 2 years), the Representative's Stake is Slashed (confiscated and burned). This offsets some of the inflationary loss.
Summary of Incentives:

Success: Representative gets 1% of revenue (Wealth).
Failure: Representative loses their Stake (Poverty).
