Here is the updated architecture for The WILL Protocol v6: The Citizen-Laborer Loop.

The "WILL" Protocol v6: The Integrated Economy
In this version, the "Vendor" from the previous step is replaced by The Citizen Workforce.

1. The Identity Layer Expansion: "Skill Tags"
Since every Voter is also a potential Laborer, the WILL NFT needs to store "Capabilities." We don't need resumes; we need attested skills.

The Mechanism: A Voter can attach "Skill Tags" to their NFT (e.g., #Welder, #Driver, #GeneralLabor, #Coder, #Accountant).
Attestation: Skills are verified by other citizens with that same tag (Peer Review) or by passing a simple quiz/practical test at a community hub.
Privacy: You can choose to make your skill profile "Public" (so Representatives can hire you) or "Private" (if you just want to vote).
2. The Representative: "Project Manager" Mode
The Representative is no longer just a politician; they are a Project Manager.

They propose the goal (e.g., "Build Community Garden").
They set the budget.
Crucially: They do not do the work alone. They must hire from the pool of Voters to execute it.
3. The Workflow: From Vote to Paycheck
Here is how a project flows from concept to completion, using only citizens:

Proposal: Representative (Project Manager) submits the "Community Garden" plan. The cost is estimated at 50,000 tokens.
Voting: Citizens with active WILL NFTs vote "Yes." Threshold met. Funds are minted into the Representative's Smart Contract.
The "Job Board": The Representative creates "Tasks" on-chain:
Task 1: Clear land (Requires 5 people, #GeneralLabor).
Task 2: Install irrigation (Requires 2 people, #Plumber).
Application: Citizens (Voters) apply for these tasks using their WILL NFTs.
Proof of Labor (The "Clock-In"):
Workers show up at the physical site.
Using P2P Proof of Presence (the same tech used for voting), the Workers and the Representative "ping" each other's phones to verify they are all at the location.
The Smart Contract logs the hours.
Payment: The Smart Contract automatically pays the Workers directly from the project funds. No boss approves a timesheet; the code pays based on verified presence + task completion.
4. The "Jury Duty" Guardrail (Preventing Fake Jobs)
If the Representative hires their 5 best friends to "dig a hole" and pays them 50,000 tokens for it, that is theft (inflation).

The Solution: Randomized Citizen Auditors (Jury Duty)

When a Task is marked "Complete," the system randomly selects 3 other Citizens (Auditors) from the local area.
They must physically visit the site within 24 hours and verify the work (e.g., scan a QR code at the garden).
If they sign off: The Workers get paid.
Incentive: Auditors are paid a small fee from the project budget for their time.
Penalty: If the Auditors find that no work was done, the Representative's Stake is slashed, the Workers are blacklisted, and the Auditors get the bounty.
5. Dangers & Issues in the "Citizen-Laborer" Model
This is the most human-centric design, but it brings human complexities.

A. The "Nepotism" Problem
Risk: Representative A gets elected. They only hire people from their specific political faction or family, ignoring skilled workers who didn't vote for them.
Fix: Blind Application Queue. The Representative sees the skills needed (e.g., "Need 1 Welder"), but the applications are anonymized until the "Proof of Presence" clock-in. Or, the system uses a First-Come-First-Serve queue for citizens with the right skills, removing the Representative's discretion in hiring.
B. The "Low Skill" Trap
Risk: The community votes to build a high-tech data center, but no one in the local citizen pool knows how to code or install servers. The project fails.
Fix: Outsourcing Protocol. If a project requires skills not available in the local Voter pool (verified by checking the NFT Skill Tags), the Representative must hire an external contractor. However, the external contractor must be "chaperoned" by a local Citizen (who gets paid to watch them), ensuring money doesn't leave the ecosystem unmonitored.
C. The "Unpaid Volunteer" Burnout
Risk: In the early days, the project might fail to generate revenue (Phase 5). Workers might work for weeks, the project fails, and they don't get their full success bonus.
Fix: Hourly Wages are guaranteed. Workers are paid for their time (Labor) immediately from the minted funds. The "Success Tax" applies to the Representative's bonus and the project's profit, but the Worker gets paid for the sweat equity regardless of the project's long-term success.
